explanation: HTML stands for HyperText Markup Language used to create web pages.

question_text: What is the basic structure of an HTML document?

correct_answer: <!DOCTYPE html> tells browser this is HTML5 document.
Root element that contains all other HTML elements.
Defines title shown in browser tab and search results.
Contains all visible content of web page.
Creates a horizontal line for thematic separation.
Generic inline container for phrasing content.
Creates hyperlink to other pages or resources: Link
Alternative text for images (for accessibility and broken images).
Defines item in list (used inside <ul> or <ol>).
Defines header cell in table (bold and centered by default).
Creates form for user input: <form action="url" method="post">
Creates multi-line text input: <textarea rows="4" cols="50"></textarea>
Defines option in dropdown list: <option value="1">One</option>

question_text: What is the for attribute in <label>?
correct_answer: for="element_id" connects label to form element.
Provides metadata about HTML document: <meta charset="UTF-8">
Links external resources like CSS: <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
Provide additional information about elements: <tag attribute="value">
Class name for styling multiple elements: <div class="container">
Using HTML elements that convey meaning: <header>
Contains main content of document (should be unique).
Content indirectly related to main content: sidebar
Represents footer for its nearest sectioning content.
Self-contained content with optional caption: images
Cites creative work: <cite>The Great Gatsby</cite> by Fitzgerald.
Inline quotation: <q>To be or not to be</q>.
Preformatted text preserving spaces and line breaks.
Represents variable in math or programming: <var>x</var> = 5
Container for drawing graphics via JavaScript.
Displays progress of a task: <progress value="70" max="100">
Represents dialog box or modal window.
Container for client-side content that can be cloned and inserted.
Placeholder in web component for user-provided content.
Represents result of calculation or user action.
Container for multiple image sources for responsive design.
Defines area inside image map: <area shape="rect" coords="...">
Specifies base URL for all relative URLs: <base href="https://example.com/">
Content shown when JavaScript is disabled.
Word break opportunity: indicates where line can break.
Isolates bidirectional text from surrounding text.
Represents ruby annotations for East Asian typography.
Ruby text component of ruby annotation.
Provides fallback parentheses for browsers without ruby support.
Links content to machine-readable translation: <data value="123">One</data>
Groups columns in table for styling.
Generates encryption key for forms (deprecated in HTML5).
Represents group of commands (semantic alternative to <ul>).
Checking HTML code follows W3C standards and rules.

question_text: What is the difference between HTML and XHTML?
correct_answer: XHTML is stricter XML-based version of HTML with stricter syntax rules.
<!-- This is a comment --> (not displayed in browser).
Specifies text direction: dir="ltr" (left-to-right) or dir="rtl" (right-to-left).
Specifies tab order of elements: tabindex="1"
Makes element editable by user: contenteditable="true"
Specifies if element is draggable: draggable="true"
Hints whether content should be translated: translate="yes"
